<@UJXP7LS78> Para HTTPS necesitas un certificado de una autoridad certificadora reconocida.
Con Let's Encrypt puedes conseguir uno gratis automáticamente que dure tres meses, y renovarlo cuando esté a punto de caducar.
Pero necesitas acceso a la configuración del servidor para poder ponerlo como HTTPS, no puedes hacerlo en un hosting.
can someone please show me how to pass a javascript variable to mod harbour.
you understand that anything mod_harbour does is in the server and anything javascript does is in the browser, right?
you can't write some javascript code, then some mod_harbour on the same page and expect that to work
that said, you can intercept a link and add a parameter to the url
or you can add a hidden field to a form and replace its content on submit
Or did you need to add a variable to an ajax call?
I am not clear about the session object.
it's not properly a javascript object
"SessionStorage", like so many other web APIs, is an interface the browser gives you
you take the SessionStorage "variable" and use it
but does harbour see the sessionStorage?
no
it's only within the browser
if you need something common to the server and the browser, you can use cookies
<@UJHD6A81H> I think you have some of the concepts wrong
all of the harbour code runs on the server, well before any of the javascript runs
at some point later, the html gets to the browser and it will start running the javascript
if you need communication between javascript and mod_harbour, that has to happen during a page request
I think the closest that I can come is using AJAX.
you can also pass GET parameters or inputs in a form
but yeah, the easiest thing is probably AJAX
(though hint, the `fetch` API is so much easier to use)
